ğŸ§  Problem Statement:
Given an array arr, find the minimum and maximum elements in the array.

âœ… Constraints:
1 <= arr.length <= 10^5

1 <= arr[i] <= 10^9

ğŸ¯ Goal:
Return a Pair<min, max> of the smallest and largest element in the array.

ğŸ” Approach:
ğŸ”¸ Step-by-Step Thinking:
Array may contain one or more elements.

We need to compare every element to determine min and max.

Since we must visit each element once, best time complexity is O(n).

We initialize min and max with the first element of the array.

Traverse the array from index 1:

If current element < min, update min.

If current element > max, update max.

ğŸ“„ Dry Run:
java
Copy
Edit
Input: [3, 2, 1, 56, 10000, 167]

Start: min = 3, max = 3

i = 1 â†’ arr[i] = 2 â†’ min = 2  
i = 2 â†’ arr[i] = 1 â†’ min = 1  
i = 3 â†’ arr[i] = 56 â†’ max = 56  
i = 4 â†’ arr[i] = 10000 â†’ max = 10000  
i = 5 â†’ arr[i] = 167 â†’ no change

Result â†’ min = 1, max = 10000
âœ… Final Code (GFG Friendly):
ğŸ”¹ Main Logic in Solution Class:
java
Copy
Edit
class Solution {
    public Pair<Integer, Integer> getMinMax(int[] arr) {
        int minimum = arr[0];
        int maximum = arr[0];

        for (int i = 1; i < arr.length; i++) {
            if (arr[i] < minimum) {
                minimum = arr[i];
            }
            if (arr[i] > maximum) {
                maximum = arr[i];
            }
        }

        return new Pair<>(minimum, maximum);
    }
}
ğŸ› ï¸ Custom Pair Class (If needed):
Use this if you're testing outside of platforms like GFG that already define Pair.

java
Copy
Edit
class Pair<U, V> {
    public final U first;
    public final V second;

    public Pair(U first, V second) {
        this.first = first;
        this.second = second;
    }
}
ğŸ• Time Complexity:
O(n) â€“ One pass through the array.

ğŸ“¦ Space Complexity:
O(1) â€“ No extra space used (except return value).

